= lesson 23: places

In the previous lesson, we looked at #strong[󱥍 pi]. As you saw, there are many
phrases with two very reasonable meanings, depending on if they have #strong[󱥍
  pi] or not. But there are also a lot of phrases which make #emph[very little
  sense] if #strong[󱥍 pi] is missing! You'll see this a lot with names:

#list((
  sentence("REPLACE", "soweli pi jan Ema", "Emma's dog"),
  sentence("REPLACE", "soweli jan Ema", "A human-like dog named Emma (???)"),
  sentence("REPLACE", "toki pi jan Mili", "Millie's speech"),
  sentence("REPLACE", "toki jan Mili", "A human language named Millie (???)"),
))

If you don't use #strong[󱥍 pi], the name instead applies to the #emph[first]
word! And that can turn out to be silly. For this reason, you will often find
#strong[󱥍 pi] near names!

You will also often find it after words that refer to locations, such as these
new ones:

#list((
  word("REPLACE", "selo", "skin, peel, shell, bark"),
  word("REPLACE", "insa", "the internal part, centre, middle"),
  word("REPLACE", "monsi", "back, rear"),
  word("REPLACE", "sinpin", "face, front, wall"),
  word("REPLACE", "anpa", "bottom; to defeat"),
))

Let's use them in some sentences:

#list((
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "selo kasi li kiwen.",
    "The bark of a tree is hard and wooden.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "selo pi kasi ni li pakala.",
    "The bark of this tree is damaged.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "soweli li lon insa tomo.",
    "The cat is inside the house.",
  ),
  sentence("REPLACE", "o tawa insa pi tomo mi!", "Go inside my house!"),
  sentence("REPLACE", "sinpin pi jan Ali li pona.", "Ali's face is nice."),
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "mani li lon anpa pi telo suli.",
    "The treasure is on the ocean floor.",
  ),
))

Protip: since #strong[󱥍 pi] only exists for rebracketing, it will never occur
before just one word! There are always two words or more after it.
